1. Class = Blueprint

A class defines what an object will look like.

Example:

class Car {

}

This is just a design.
No car exists yet.

Think:

Class = blueprint of a car
Object = actual car built from blueprint
2. Fields (Object Data)

Fields describe what the object stores.

They go inside the class but outside methods.

Example:

class Car {

    private String make;
    private String color;
    private int doors;

}

These are properties of every car.

Example objects:

Car1 → make=Tesla color=Black doors=4
Car2 → make=Porsche color=Red doors=2

Each object has its own copy.

Rule:

Fields → inside class
Fields → outside methods
3. Methods (Object Behaviour)

Methods describe what the object can do.

Example:

class Car {

    private String make;

    public void setMake(String make){
        this.make = make;
    }

}

This method changes the state of the object.

Rule:

Methods → inside class
Methods → outside other methods

You cannot place a method inside another method.

4. Methods Contain Statements

Inside methods you write actual executable code.

Example:

public void setMake(String make){
    this.make = make;
}

Inside the method:

assignment
calculations
conditions
loops
5. main() Method (Program Entry)

Java programs start from:

public static void main(String[] args)

This method is where you create objects and run code.

Example:

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args){

        Car car1 = new Car();
        car1.setMake("Tesla");

    }
}

Flow:

Program starts
↓
main() runs
↓
object created
↓
methods called
6. Full Structure (Most Important Part)

A normal class looks like this:

class Example {

    // 1 Fields
    int a;
    int b;

    // 2 Methods
    void setA(int value){
        a = value;
    }

    int getSum(){
        return a + b;
    }

}

Structure:

Class
 ├── Fields
 └── Methods
       └── Statements
7. Where Objects Are Created

Objects are usually created inside main() or another method.

Example:

public class Test {

    public static void main(String[] args){

        SimpleCalculator calc = new SimpleCalculator();

    }

}

Here:

Class SimpleCalculator → blueprint
calc → actual object
8. Simple Visual Model

Think like this:

CLASS
 ├─ Fields (data)
 │    make
 │    doors
 │
 ├─ Methods (behaviour)
 │    setMake()
 │    getMake()
 │
 └─ main() (runs program)

9. Example Using Your Calculator

Blueprint:

class SimpleCalculator {

    double firstNumber;
    double secondNumber;

    double getAdditionResult(){
        return firstNumber + secondNumber;
    }

}

Running code:

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args){

        SimpleCalculator calc = new SimpleCalculator();

        calc.firstNumber = 5;
        calc.secondNumber = 4;

        System.out.println(calc.getAdditionResult());

    }

}

Output: 9

10. Quick Rule That Removes 90% of Confusion

Ask yourself:

Question	Where it goes
What data does an object store?	Field
What can the object do?	Method
Where does the program start?	main()
Where do objects get created?	inside methods